WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:05.300
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:22.590 --> 00:00:25.210
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: Good
evening, I'm Anne McLean,

00:00:25.210 --> 00:00:27.830
from the library's music
division and it is my pleasure

00:00:27.830 --> 00:00:31.400
to welcome composer Gabriela
Lena Frank to the Library

00:00:31.400 --> 00:00:33.930
of Congress tonight and
also Harry Christophers,

00:00:33.930 --> 00:00:35.760
who is the artistic
director of the Haydn and --

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:37.700
Handel and Haydn Society.

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:40.220
Very, very excited to
have you both with us.

00:00:40.220 --> 00:00:41.520
Thank you for coming.

00:00:41.520 --> 00:00:46.310 position:56%
This a very special concert
tonight, featuring the famous Handel

00:00:46.310 --> 00:00:50.920
and Haydn Society and also a new
work co-commissioned by the Society

00:00:50.920 --> 00:00:52.470
and the Library of Congress.

00:00:52.470 --> 00:00:55.070
We've been looking forward
to this for quite a while.

00:00:55.070 --> 00:00:58.730
The work was co-commissioned
by these two institutions

00:00:58.730 --> 00:01:00.930 position:56%
to mark our milestone anniversaries,

00:01:00.930 --> 00:01:05.050
it's our 90th as a concert
presenter since 1925.

00:01:05.050 --> 00:01:09.110
And H&amp;H, the nations oldest
continuously performing arts

00:01:09.110 --> 00:01:12.400
organization, is celebrating
its bicentennial.

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:14.870
This is the Washington
premier and it was heard

00:01:14.870 --> 00:01:17.840
for the very first time
last June in Boston

00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:22.140
by a very chorus centric audience
at the Chorus America conference.

00:01:22.140 --> 00:01:23.960
What was that evening like for you?

00:01:23.960 --> 00:01:25.260
&gt;&gt; Harry Christophers:
It was brilliant.

00:01:25.260 --> 00:01:28.930
I mean, H&amp;H, we hosted Chorus
American in Boston and performed

00:01:28.930 --> 00:01:33.280
in Symphony Hall, a program, a
very mixed program of some Handel,

00:01:33.280 --> 00:01:36.050
I think we did part- we
did some Messiah, I believe

00:01:36.050 --> 00:01:41.380
and Gabriela has a wonderful piece
and we also did [inaudible 1:41].

00:01:41.380 --> 00:01:44.780
It was a mixture particularly
devised for Chorus America

00:01:44.780 --> 00:01:50.090
and all the delegates and choral
conductors and singers there.

00:01:50.090 --> 00:01:52.960
&gt;&gt; You know, we were looking,
I was showing them just now,

00:01:52.960 --> 00:01:56.990
we have a book, we have a
complete run of all the books

00:01:56.990 --> 00:02:03.900
of pieces collected by the society,
and it began in 1815, right?

00:02:03.900 --> 00:02:05.370
&gt;&gt; Harry Christophers: Yes, the
society gave its first concert

00:02:05.370 --> 00:02:08.720
on Christmas Day 1815 in
Kings Chapel in Boston,

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:13.020
in which there were pieces by
Handel and Haydn, of course.

00:02:13.020 --> 00:02:14.840
And why it was called that was

00:02:14.840 --> 00:02:16.790
because Handel was the
old and Haydn was the new.

00:02:16.790 --> 00:02:19.510
Haydn died a few years.

00:02:19.510 --> 00:02:21.910
So it was very simple.

00:02:21.910 --> 00:02:24.670
But what's interesting
about these pieces and --

00:02:24.670 --> 00:02:25.970
do we talk about this volume?

00:02:25.970 --> 00:02:30.350
That what people don't know is
that H&amp;H was a publishing company.

00:02:30.350 --> 00:02:34.400
And in 1825, 1827, 1830, they
published various things,

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:37.570
and one of these is called
the Old Colony Collection.

00:02:37.570 --> 00:02:41.300
And I was fascinated
by it because I had

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:46.110
with my group I founded
nearly 16 years ago,

00:02:46.110 --> 00:02:49.960 position:56%
we recorded the complete Eaton Choir
Book, which dates from, of course,

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:52.340
1490, a few years before.

00:02:52.340 --> 00:02:54.310
But this, you know,
for a young country,

00:02:54.310 --> 00:02:56.810
this is quite a publication.

00:02:56.810 --> 00:03:02.770 position:56%
And it contains choruses from, a
lot of Handel choruses from Messiah,

00:03:02.770 --> 00:03:06.460
Israel and Egypt, Judas
[inaudible], Joshua.

00:03:06.460 --> 00:03:09.710
But then, a whole lot of what
I can term sort of late sort

00:03:09.710 --> 00:03:12.060
of Chapel Royal verse anthems

00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:16.600
by very well known composers
called Kent and Chapel.

00:03:17.750 --> 00:03:19.150
Does anybody know them?

00:03:19.150 --> 00:03:21.660
No. Well, not does
anybody in England either.

00:03:21.660 --> 00:03:26.130
But what was amazing is that these
people were clearly they were the

00:03:26.130 --> 00:03:30.230
best, the Howells of the
choral world in 1780,

00:03:30.230 --> 00:03:32.530
between about 1780 and 1800.

00:03:32.530 --> 00:03:35.670
And there's a piece by Kent
we're performing this evening,

00:03:35.670 --> 00:03:38.790
Hear my Prayer, that was actually
very, very popular at that time.

00:03:38.790 --> 00:03:40.690
Nobody possesses it
today in England.

00:03:40.690 --> 00:03:43.320
There's no cathedral choir
that has it in their library.

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:47.110
But it was last published in a
collection for Durham Cathedral

00:03:47.110 --> 00:03:50.410
in about 1843, but not performed.

00:03:50.410 --> 00:03:54.750
But here they are preserved in
the Old Colony Collection here.

00:03:54.750 --> 00:03:57.000
So you'll witness one
or two of those pieces.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.100
And also, you'll recognize,
there's a piece

00:03:59.100 --> 00:04:06.060 position:56%
by a person called Mozart two sacred
words, and no prizes, I'm afraid,

00:04:06.060 --> 00:04:11.640
for guessing where the tune comes
from, but you'll hear it tonight.

00:04:11.640 --> 00:04:13.790
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: You know, you'll
have to go backstage in a moment,

00:04:13.790 --> 00:04:16.840
so we will start with you and
ask you a couple of questions.

00:04:16.840 --> 00:04:20.800
With your own ensemble,
the 16, which Harry founded

00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:24.160
and has an extraordinary
reputation around the world,

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:26.860
you achieved such an
expressive simplicity.

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:30.030
And I saw a statement from
you somewhere where you said,

00:04:30.030 --> 00:04:33.920
"We shape the phrases according
to the architecture of the time,

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:36.920
allowing the music to have
the freedom that it did then."

00:04:36.920 --> 00:04:39.370
Supplied so beautifully that
this program, all the programs,

00:04:39.370 --> 00:04:42.170
you're doing new work, old work.

00:04:42.170 --> 00:04:44.750
&gt;&gt; Harry Christophers: Well, I
mean, so much of the work I do

00:04:44.750 --> 00:04:47.590
in England is [inaudible] music,
and of course, that's sacred music

00:04:47.590 --> 00:04:51.540
that the composers of the day
wrote the music with the buildings

00:04:51.540 --> 00:04:54.330
in mind just the same as
the building, builders,

00:04:54.330 --> 00:04:57.420
of those wonderful cathedrals
all throughout Europe built the

00:04:57.420 --> 00:04:58.990
cathedrals with the music in mind,

00:04:58.990 --> 00:05:01.430
there were definite
ratios that were going on.

00:05:01.430 --> 00:05:04.420
And so, you know, to
fit that is lovely.

00:05:04.420 --> 00:05:08.540 position:56%
And when we talk about architecture,
I mean, architecture music,

00:05:08.540 --> 00:05:12.420
the whole idea of the arch phrase,
goes right through from [inaudible]

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:14.740
through Baroque right
through to early classical,

00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:17.090
and really I suppose
and with Beethoven,

00:05:17.090 --> 00:05:19.010
etcetera, things began to change.

00:05:19.010 --> 00:05:23.060
But really we can use that
idea of architecture and shape

00:05:23.060 --> 00:05:27.610
of phrases right through certainly
into early Mozart and Haydn.

00:05:27.610 --> 00:05:28.910
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: It's wonderful

00:05:28.910 --> 00:05:31.850
to have Gabriela's
piece on this program.

00:05:31.850 --> 00:05:36.410 position:56%
We are pleased to have been working
with [inaudible] and with the Handel

00:05:36.410 --> 00:05:39.380
and Haydn Society for two years

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:42.200
in the past years to
make this possible.

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:45.810
And have had a number, of
course, discussions about it.

00:05:45.810 --> 00:05:49.590
It's string quintet and
full chorus of 26, right?

00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:51.490
And tell us about the text.

00:05:51.490 --> 00:05:52.790
We were talking about this earlier.

00:05:52.790 --> 00:05:54.880
Ralph Waldo Emerson.

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:56.350
&gt;&gt; Harry Christophers: Well,
it was interesting, wasn't it?

00:05:56.350 --> 00:05:58.750
Because having a commission
bicentennial,

00:05:58.750 --> 00:06:03.710
we really pondered a lot about
what to do with the text.

00:06:03.710 --> 00:06:09.300 position:56%
And I said, it's got to be something
that was really relative to Boston.

00:06:09.300 --> 00:06:10.600
And somebody said, well,

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:12.510
there's this amazing thing
called the Boston Hymn.

00:06:12.510 --> 00:06:14.440
I'd never heard it, but it's
incredibly long, isn't it?

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:15.740
I mean, it's by Emerson.

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:17.200
What, it's about three pages long.

00:06:17.200 --> 00:06:18.500
&gt;&gt; Gabriela Lena Frank:
Something like that.

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:20.650
And I remember in our
initial discussion,

00:06:20.650 --> 00:06:24.820
that I led a very good team on
board, very first [inaudible].

00:06:24.820 --> 00:06:28.700 position:56%
I was pulling it up on the
Internet in that conversation we had

00:06:28.700 --> 00:06:31.310
over the phone, there were
several of us sharing that.

00:06:31.310 --> 00:06:33.780
And I remember looking and going,
oh my god, and they only want this

00:06:33.780 --> 00:06:37.170
to be 15, 18 minutes,
and I said this is --

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:39.520
plus you know, possible
instrumental interlude.

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:43.000
We were already tossing out
our wish list of attributes

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:44.550
that could to go into the music.

00:06:44.550 --> 00:06:48.730
So I remember thinking, okay, you
know, I'm an editor's daughter,

00:06:48.730 --> 00:06:50.890
so I should be able to get
into this text and be able

00:06:50.890 --> 00:06:53.220
to pull out salient elements.

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:56.390
But doing just a simple
surgical exerting wasn't going

00:06:56.390 --> 00:07:00.020
to really do well because the text,
if you know it, is very linear.

00:07:00.020 --> 00:07:01.930
So if you have to just
remove a verse,

00:07:01.930 --> 00:07:03.760
it suddenly doesn't make sense.

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:07.800
So what you need to do is go
to each one and distill it

00:07:07.800 --> 00:07:10.800
down a little bit more, and
then it actually makes sense.

00:07:10.800 --> 00:07:13.610
If you get rid of some of
the details that trip you up

00:07:13.610 --> 00:07:16.100
and just get it down
to the bare-bones.

00:07:16.100 --> 00:07:19.430
And then it's also
a bit of a sermon.

00:07:19.430 --> 00:07:22.540
Now, sermons don't
necessarily lend themselves well

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:25.270
to song, but lyrics do.

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:29.640 position:56%
So was there a type of lyricized
sermon that I can make so I preserve

00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:34.140 position:56%
that sense of foretelling the future
when you get away from tyranny.

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:37.420
I mean, it was very, very important
to keep that sense of grandeur

00:07:37.420 --> 00:07:40.830
and that sense of awareness
of the past that Emerson had,

00:07:40.830 --> 00:07:44.440
but also the optimism that
he had for the future.

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:49.150
So we worked out something where I
was able to distill the text down.

00:07:49.150 --> 00:07:51.450
And then to give a
very prominent role,

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:53.070 position:56%
you'll see, to the instrumentalists.

00:07:53.070 --> 00:07:56.390
They tell the story I
think equal to the singers.

00:07:56.390 --> 00:07:57.690
&gt;&gt; Harry Christophers: Yes,

00:07:57.690 --> 00:08:00.410
and actually what Gabriela's
done is achieved a wonderfully --

00:08:00.410 --> 00:08:04.530
to say it's an archaic sound
with the singers isn't quite --

00:08:04.530 --> 00:08:08.510 position:56%
it sounds very colonial, it really
does capture, I just feel, you know,

00:08:08.510 --> 00:08:12.640
as soon as the singers come in,
it captures something about 18,

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:15.240
the early 1800s and it's amazing.

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:21.350
[inaudible] there are no kings and
that sort of stuff, which is good.

00:08:21.350 --> 00:08:23.370
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: About the text
itself, it's very compelling.

00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:26.470
It doesn't refer, it
refers to slavery and that

00:08:26.470 --> 00:08:30.870
of course is a very important issue
of the day of his, Emerson's day.

00:08:30.870 --> 00:08:34.730
What, what were the
phrases, I want to ask you

00:08:34.730 --> 00:08:36.770
about the recitative-like quality.

00:08:36.770 --> 00:08:39.820
Somebody had noticed that there
were certain moments that have

00:08:39.820 --> 00:08:41.920
that quality and the
diction is incredible.

00:08:41.920 --> 00:08:43.730
I heard the recording
of the premiere.

00:08:43.730 --> 00:08:46.640
Well, that's what you're known for,
that's what, among other things,

00:08:46.640 --> 00:08:48.840
that's what the Society
is known for,

00:08:48.840 --> 00:08:52.130 position:56%
is carrying the word so beautifully.

00:08:52.130 --> 00:08:56.290
Are you thinking of recording
it, perhaps, at some point?

00:08:56.290 --> 00:08:57.590
&gt;&gt; Harry Christophers: I don't
know, we'll, we'll have to see.

00:08:57.590 --> 00:08:59.820
We'll have to see if
it's in the future.

00:08:59.820 --> 00:09:02.130
I think it's -- something you
mentioned, just about the words,

00:09:02.130 --> 00:09:05.760
I mean, the fact that this text,
of course, is so, is so powerful

00:09:05.760 --> 00:09:07.960
and so powerful to America.

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:11.270
And, one of the things
of this concert is just

00:09:11.270 --> 00:09:14.490
after Gabriela's piece we
have pieces by William Byrd,

00:09:14.490 --> 00:09:18.480
which of course, are
incredibly powerful to, you know,

00:09:18.480 --> 00:09:22.420
it's from the, you know, era of the
of, of post-Reformation in England

00:09:22.420 --> 00:09:25.640
when Catholics lived
in fear of their life.

00:09:25.640 --> 00:09:28.670
And you'll see that actually
what I, there's a modest elegy

00:09:28.670 --> 00:09:30.120
to Thomas Tallis by William Byrd.

00:09:30.120 --> 00:09:33.420
But then I've also, for the
[inaudible] you'll notice I,

00:09:33.420 --> 00:09:36.160
I've just had, I will have
four singers, just at the side

00:09:36.160 --> 00:09:40.540
of the stage, singing this in a
very intimate way because they --

00:09:40.540 --> 00:09:43.670
and Byrd wrote those
masses for private use.

00:09:43.670 --> 00:09:46.270
They weren't for singing, well,
they weren't allowed to be sung

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:48.390
in the bigger theaters because
they were in Latin, of course.

00:09:48.390 --> 00:09:51.880
But they would have been sung
in, in a private house, Rectors

00:09:51.880 --> 00:09:54.940
and Catholics, getting
together, worshiping in private

00:09:54.940 --> 00:09:57.210
and if Thomas Cromwell
had knocked at the door,

00:09:57.210 --> 00:09:58.610 position:56%
their heads would have been cut off.

00:09:58.610 --> 00:10:01.090
I mean it's, it's, it's, you
know, this was powerful stuff.

00:10:01.090 --> 00:10:03.880
So just in the same
way that your piece

00:10:03.880 --> 00:10:07.680
in the Boston Hymn is very
powerful, we know we can reflect

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:10.630
that way back 400 years
to, to England.

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:11.930
&gt;&gt; Gabriela Lena Frank: I remember,

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:14.050
what I wanted to convey
too was a real fine line.

00:10:14.050 --> 00:10:19.150 position:56%
I wanted to celebrate and to be
glorious when we get to that moment.

00:10:19.150 --> 00:10:22.820
But to also count, to hint that the
tyranny that he is referring to.

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:28.280
So there is some rather dark
writing and dark harmonies,

00:10:28.280 --> 00:10:30.910
and you have to go there as
a player, you can't eschew

00:10:30.910 --> 00:10:34.240
that in the drama as
much higher as a result.

00:10:34.240 --> 00:10:37.400
It may not be that obvious
when you look at the sermon.

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:40.330
And it was when I distilled
it that I saw the jewels

00:10:40.330 --> 00:10:42.220
and these lines that
were coming out.

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:45.450
And I was like, this is really
high, it's almost operatic.

00:10:45.450 --> 00:10:46.870
It's just high drama.

00:10:46.870 --> 00:10:48.820
But he had that kind of feeling.

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:51.800
So that raised the
bar when I saw that,

00:10:51.800 --> 00:10:53.840
that there's a lot
of levels to this.

00:10:53.840 --> 00:11:00.150
So can I come up with music that
likewise has those kinds of levels.

00:11:00.150 --> 00:11:04.070
&gt;&gt; Anne McLean: I was thinking, you
mentioned earlier that the writing

00:11:04.070 --> 00:11:09.700
for the voices at some point I saw
something referenced to low voices

00:11:09.700 --> 00:11:13.760
and high voices, would you
expand on that a little bit.

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:17.920
&gt;&gt; Gabriela Lena Frank: Well,
for me a choir is an orchestra.

00:11:17.920 --> 00:11:20.320
It's not just voices and
it's not just [inaudible].

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:22.630
There's the color blend.

00:11:22.630 --> 00:11:26.010
We talk about sopranos
and we talk about altos,

00:11:26.010 --> 00:11:27.740
and yes there's a slight
[inaudible],

00:11:27.740 --> 00:11:30.980
different color, that's
very important.

00:11:30.980 --> 00:11:33.860
And of course, a woman
can sing a note

00:11:33.860 --> 00:11:36.330
that a man sings the exact
same note at the same octave

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:38.180
and it's a completely
different color,

00:11:38.180 --> 00:11:40.820
one that's instantly
recognizable by anyone.

00:11:40.820 --> 00:11:45.340
So the interplay of low and high
is an easy way to separate verses.

00:11:45.340 --> 00:11:49.970
You can just assign now girls,
now boys, now boys, now girls.

00:11:49.970 --> 00:11:51.500
But then you can also blend.

00:11:51.500 --> 00:11:55.390
So there's an innate kind of
drama of teaming up and separating

00:11:55.390 --> 00:11:57.260
that can be very effective.

00:11:57.260 --> 00:12:00.960 position:56%
And Emerson has that too, there's
certain lines that are higher drama,

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:05.520
other lines that are almost like a
Greek chorus, that are commenting,

00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:07.040
some lines advance the plot,

00:12:07.040 --> 00:12:10.320
others make the metaphorical
elusion to something in nature.

00:12:10.320 --> 00:12:13.630
It's expensive when you
make an elution to nature

00:12:13.630 --> 00:12:17.100
to make the lyrics pretty,
but if they can also double up

00:12:17.100 --> 00:12:20.560
and advance the plot at the
same time, for me that's almost

00:12:20.560 --> 00:12:22.020
like combining high and low voices.

00:12:22.020 --> 00:12:25.060
So you can see how he's
orchestrating with colors

00:12:25.060 --> 00:12:27.190
and intentions at the same time.

00:12:27.190 --> 00:12:30.950
So I like, you know, symphonically
when I write for the choir,

00:12:30.950 --> 00:12:33.710
and some people say I write
vocally for the symphony,

00:12:33.710 --> 00:12:36.390
so I think you find
that common ground.

00:12:36.390 --> 00:12:37.690
&gt;&gt; Harry Christophers:
It's interesting

00:12:37.690 --> 00:12:39.820
because actually also
you're cast writing,

00:12:39.820 --> 00:12:42.100
the string writing is very,
very different, is it?

00:12:42.100 --> 00:12:47.160
And it's very -- I mean, there's
kind of the sort of folk elements

00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:51.430
that come into it, which
where did they come from?

00:12:51.430 --> 00:12:52.730
&gt;&gt; Gabriela Lena Frank: Yes.

