And if you've read anything in
my bio, you'll know that I'm not

00:12:56.330 --> 00:13:00.760
from Boston, and I have a
Jewish Lithuanian forebears,

00:13:00.760 --> 00:13:03.370
Chinese forebears, and
Peruvian forebears.

00:13:03.370 --> 00:13:07.620
And then I was born in Berkeley
in 1972, and hit Berkeley,

00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:08.920
you know, hippie hay day.

00:13:08.920 --> 00:13:15.980
So I am very I represent a lot
of Americans in my generation.

00:13:15.980 --> 00:13:22.040
And in my life as I have studied
musica Indian, Indian music,

00:13:22.040 --> 00:13:25.770
of Bolivia, Equador, Peru, and
looking at the colonial music too

00:13:25.770 --> 00:13:30.310
that has come over, I've also made
a study casually, very casually,

00:13:30.310 --> 00:13:33.630
of folk music of the
world, of other cultures.

00:13:33.630 --> 00:13:36.080
And there's certain
gestures that just seem to be

00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:38.450
of the people that come up.

00:13:38.450 --> 00:13:42.160
There's a kind of lift, there's
a kind of grace note phrasing

00:13:42.160 --> 00:13:44.290
that seem to lend themselves
well to flutes.

00:13:44.290 --> 00:13:46.060
And we have flutes everywhere.

00:13:46.060 --> 00:13:48.880
And I mean, this is a
very general observation,

00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:53.320
and even people listening to
music of mine that is not Indian,

00:13:53.320 --> 00:13:55.930
this is not an Indian work,
they still see the things that I

00:13:55.930 --> 00:13:59.710
like to do in my ostensibly
Indian influence works.

00:13:59.710 --> 00:14:03.540
So one of the things I
noticed the folkloric groups,

00:14:03.540 --> 00:14:05.270
there a lot of solos.

00:14:05.270 --> 00:14:06.570 position:56%
There's something about the intimacy

00:14:06.570 --> 00:14:10.110
of the three other players backing
off and one player coming forward.

00:14:10.110 --> 00:14:12.430
And have that in this
kind of writing.

00:14:12.430 --> 00:14:14.520
There's something vocal
about the line.

00:14:14.520 --> 00:14:16.610
And you have a lot of that
in the string writing,

00:14:16.610 --> 00:14:18.260
where one player just
starts going off

00:14:18.260 --> 00:14:20.390
and just got this very
expressive feeling.

00:14:20.390 --> 00:14:24.090
For me that is of the people,
it's something very much

00:14:24.090 --> 00:14:26.800
of the populace mindset,
expressing yourself that way.

00:14:26.800 --> 00:14:32.460
The harmonies, sort of,
sort of, open harmonies.

00:14:32.460 --> 00:14:36.490
Dismisses are usually
inflected folkloric music.

00:14:36.490 --> 00:14:38.500
A lot of people think the
harmonies are very simple,

00:14:38.500 --> 00:14:41.740
if you only look the primary
notes of the melodies.

00:14:41.740 --> 00:14:43.110
But if you look at
all the little notes,

00:14:43.110 --> 00:14:45.500 position:56%
they do getting into the main notes.

00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:50.070
Instead of going [note sounds],
they might go [note sounds].

00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:52.680
All the little notes
that are characteristic

00:14:52.680 --> 00:14:54.690
of one region over another.

00:14:54.690 --> 00:14:59.240
They're often not that consonant,
and that's what enriches the music.

00:14:59.240 --> 00:15:01.540
Actually, for me, it's a bit
like seeing a very nice sweater

00:15:01.540 --> 00:15:04.600
and it comes with that tag,
and saying that, you know,

00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:07.690
the variations in the
fabric are not blemishes,

00:15:07.690 --> 00:15:09.030
it's what makes it interesting.

00:15:09.030 --> 00:15:10.710
Yet it's still a sweater.

00:15:10.710 --> 00:15:14.860
But the so-called blemishes I think
are the most interesting aspects

00:15:14.860 --> 00:15:16.160
of folkloric music.

00:15:16.160 --> 00:15:17.460
And there's plenty of that.

00:15:17.460 --> 00:15:20.680
I write it out, I don't leave it
for the player at their discretion

00:15:20.680 --> 00:15:23.080
